<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06053a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06053a">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06053a"> 53(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Ss sociale <font face="wake">T</font> solitary (en toy)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Le jeu para&icirc;t &ecirc;tre un excellent moyen de <i>culture de la sensibilit&eacute;</i>. Il d&eacute;veloppe d&apos;abord <mark>l&apos;<i>instinct social</i> ou <i>altruiste</i></mark>. &hellip; Il est &hellip; un jouet qui, &agrave; lui seul, tient lieu de soci&eacute;t&eacute; &agrave; l&apos;enfant et r&eacute;pond particuli&egrave;rement &agrave; son besoin d&apos;aimer: c&apos;est sa poup&eacute;e. <font color="green">[&hellip; Les enfants <mark>solitaires</mark> et imaginatifs vont jusqu&apos;&agrave; se cr&eacute;er des compagnons mythiques. [The game seems to be an excellent way of cultivating sensitivity. He first develops the social or altruistic instinct. ... He is ... a toy that, by itself, takes the place of society to the child and responds particularly to his need to love: it is his doll. ... Solitary and imaginative children go so far as to create mythical companions.]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 108f.</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
